<Link id="l00404" /><CodeLine lineNumber="404"><Highlight kind="comment">/// An ID used in the DbgOpIDMap (below) to lookup a stored DbgOp. This is used</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00405" /><CodeLine lineNumber="405"><Highlight kind="comment">/// in place of actual DbgOps inside of a DbgValue to reduce its size, as</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00406" /><CodeLine lineNumber="406"><Highlight kind="comment">/// DbgValue is very frequently used and passed around, and the actual DbgOp is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00407" /><CodeLine lineNumber="407"><Highlight kind="comment">/// over 8x larger than this class, due to storing a MachineOperand. This ID</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00408" /><CodeLine lineNumber="408"><Highlight kind="comment">/// should be equal for all equal DbgOps, and also encodes whether the mapped</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00409" /><CodeLine lineNumber="409"><Highlight kind="comment">/// DbgOp is a constant, meaning that for simple equality or const-ness checks</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00410" /><CodeLine lineNumber="410"><Highlight kind="comment">/// it is not necessary to lookup this ID.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Tracker for what values are in machine locations. Listens to the Things</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00656" /><CodeLine lineNumber="656"><Highlight kind="comment">/// being Done by various instructions, and maintains a table of what machine</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00657" /><CodeLine lineNumber="657"><Highlight kind="comment">/// locations have what values (as defined by a ValueIDNum).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00658" /><CodeLine lineNumber="658"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00659" /><CodeLine lineNumber="659"><Highlight kind="comment">/// There are potentially a much larger number of machine locations on the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00660" /><CodeLine lineNumber="660"><Highlight kind="comment">/// target machine than the actual working-set size of the function. On x86 for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00661" /><CodeLine lineNumber="661"><Highlight kind="comment">/// example, we&#39;re extremely unlikely to want to track values through control</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00662" /><CodeLine lineNumber="662"><Highlight kind="comment">/// or debug registers. To avoid doing so, MLocTracker has several layers of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><Highlight kind="comment">/// indirection going on, described below, to avoid unnecessarily tracking</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00664" /><CodeLine lineNumber="664"><Highlight kind="comment">/// any location.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00665" /><CodeLine lineNumber="665"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00666" /><CodeLine lineNumber="666"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Here&#39;s a sort of diagram of the indexes, read from the bottom up:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00667" /><CodeLine lineNumber="667"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00668" /><CodeLine lineNumber="668"><Highlight kind="comment">///           Size on stack   Offset on stack</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00669" /><CodeLine lineNumber="669"><Highlight kind="comment">///                 \\              /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00670" /><CodeLine lineNumber="670"><Highlight kind="comment">///          Stack Idx (Where in slot is this?)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><Highlight kind="comment">///                         /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><Highlight kind="comment">///                        /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Slot Num (%stack.0)   /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><Highlight kind="comment">/// FrameIdx =&gt; SpillNum /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><Highlight kind="comment">///              \\      /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><Highlight kind="comment">///           SpillID (int)   Register number (int)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><Highlight kind="comment">///                      \\       /</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><Highlight kind="comment">///                      LocationID =&gt; LocIdx</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><Highlight kind="comment">///                                |</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><Highlight kind="comment">///                       LocIdx =&gt; ValueIDNum</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The aim here is that the LocIdx =&gt; ValueIDNum vector is just an array of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><Highlight kind="comment">/// values in numbered locations, so that later analyses can ignore whether the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><Highlight kind="comment">/// location is a register or otherwise. To map a register / spill location to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a LocIdx, you have to use the (sparse) LocationID =&gt; LocIdx map. And to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><Highlight kind="comment">/// build a LocationID for a stack slot, you need to combine identifiers for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><Highlight kind="comment">/// which stack slot it is and where within that slot is being described.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Register mask operands cause trouble by technically defining every register;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690"><Highlight kind="comment">/// various hacks are used to avoid tracking registers that are never read and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><Highlight kind="comment">/// only written by regmasks.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00692" /><CodeLine lineNumber="692" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/livedebugvalues/mloctracker"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/livedebugvalues/mloctracker/#ae118b50388837cac4d807896b91f111e">MLocTracker</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00693" /><CodeLine lineNumber="693"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00694" /><CodeLine lineNumber="694" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/livedebugvalues/mloctracker/#ae1a29742ce2fd47f4b4769dfe5a44f9e"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/machinefunction">MachineFunction</a> &amp;<a href="/docs/api/classes/livedebugvalues/mloctracker/#ae1a29742ce2fd47f4b4769dfe5a44f9e">MF</a>;</Highlight></CodeLine>
